      "id": 1,
      "text": "Boston was founded on Shawmut Peninsula in 1630 by Puritans who named it after Boston, Lincolnshire, England.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1,
        9
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Puritan ethics and the 1629 Cambridge Agreement shaped Boston’s early governance and education focus.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2,
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Boston Public Library, founded in 1852, was the first free library in the United States.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "America’s first public school, Boston Latin School, opened in 1635 and still educates students today.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Back Bay was created by filling the city’s original hills and Needham gravel, now home to landmarks like the Boston Public Library and Trinity Church.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        13,
        14
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Boston’s Bluebikes bikeshare, launched in 2011 as Hubway, lets riders zip around the city on electric bikes.",
